I want to quickly clarify what our infrastructure looks like: we have a self-hosted 2 node HA cluster in AWS which I am referring to as our cloud deployment
column2: and a single node self-hosted deployment in the datacenter in our office which is the on prem deployment.
the appropriate rules have been set up to allow communication between our cloud environments and on prem datacenters. I had anticipated that if there were going to be problems
column3: it would be on prem trying to contact the cloud resources
column4: but instead it is the other way around.

column1: I did identify an issue with our AWS environment where it could not resolve the FQDN of the on prem instance and have since fixed that issue. From the cloud instances I can successfully ping the on prem instance using the FQDN
column2: and nmap reports that http and https ports are open
column6: and 8082. Using curl is also successful.

column1: Cc: Andrew Schneider <andrew.schneider@gearbox.com>; Sarah Moore <sarah.moore@gearbox.com>; Steve.Fortier@gearbox.co
Subject: [#187317] SUPPORT - Request For Linking Deployments & Setting Up Replication
Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.
My name is Andrew and I will be assisting you with this adding platform deployment issue.
I see that you're following the Managing Platform Deployment guide
column2: which is good information. During your connection attempts
column3: there is an issue with the connection from your SaaS instance and you're getting an error returned "Connection was successful. Unable to resolve service version."

column2: this error appears to be misleading. Currently
column3: the above error message will display
column4: even if we don't actually successfully connect to the Artifactory instance. In past instances with this error
column5: customers found that there was a slight issue with the URL being provided
column6: and modifying it to the correct URL resolved the issue. We have an internal JIRA (JFUI-6895) logged to change the error text to more properly represent what is actually happening during the connection failure.

column1: An important note here is that the SaaS instance needs to have web access to the Artifactory on-prem server. If you're using an internal hostname or have the Artifactory instance behind a reverse proxy
column2: the Artifactory instance needs to be accessible through the web. The Artifactory SaaS instance will not have access to your internal network
column3: so the reverse proxy will need to be accessible outside of your internal network.

column1: If your on-prem instance is hosted on AWS
column2: then you can use the AWS PrivateLink<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Setting+up+AWS+PrivateLinks#SettingupAWSPrivateLinks-Overview> guide to link your AWS VPC to the JFrog PrivateLink
column3: which should allow for two way traffic between the two instances.

column1: Please let me know if you have any questions regarding the information I provided above.

column2: we have a very descriptive white paper<https://jfrog.com/whitepaper/replication-using-artifactory-to-manage-binaries-across-multi-site-topologies> that describes all forms of replication that Artifactory supports. The paper is long
column3: but is very detailed and should help you with understanding each of the replication modes
column4: as well as how to implement them between your instances. Please feel free to let me know if you have any questions related to this as well.

column1: I look forward to working with you on this issue
column2: please let me know how else I can assist.

column2: Replying back to your question.
we are POCing the following scenario:

column1: We have a EC2 instance on AWS where we have installed JFrog CLI.We have a corn job on the EC2 instance that set to run every day at 1AMThe CLI command downloads log files from jfrog-log repo that were created in the last 24hWe have another cron job to extract logs from gz archive and placed them in the directory that splunk universal forwarder is monitoring.Splunk Universal forwarder is then sending the files content to splunkSince this is not the best way of using EC2 instance we were thinking on setting this up on a lambda scheduled to run once a day.Now that lambda would need to:download the files from jfrogstore them on S3 where we already have a mechanism that is responsible of sending them to Splunk ( not part of this discussion)

The lambda part is something that we are trying to investigate.To match what we do on EC2 intl lambda - getting logs using JFrog CLI we would need to have it installed every time we spin up lambda. You probably agree with me that CLI on lambda might not be the best choice.
Would you be able to help me figure out the best set of API calls to download artefacts created in last 24h ?THanks
Hope you had a great Thanksgiving! I wanted to let you know that we're still discussing internally. I will continue to provide you with updates.

column2: user already exits will not be able to access the profile page even if you turn on the settings in LDAP settings. The only way to do this is by editing users settings ( we should avoid deleting the user as it will force a new apikey ). However
column3: it's not feasible for the scope of all users.

column2: we first tired to export user access data and modify the updatable_profile. However
column3: the import process seems to be sticking or talking a long time.

column1: A faster way would be to make direct changes to the database. As discussed
column2: please take a db snapshot and ask your DBA to perform the following query:
prop_key
column3: prop_value FROM access_users_custom_data as o where o.prop_key = 'updatable_profile';

column1: UPDATE access_users_custom_data SET prop_value = true where prop_key='updatable_profile';
Let us know if your user can access profile pages after this. Thank you.

column2: it does look like you ran into this bug XRAY-7294 - "Files may not be indexed and other updates lost when RabbitMQ fails to receive messages that were resolved in 3.23.0". This most likely caused the build components to be mis-mapped and further builds would reuse this mis-mapping which was why the issue escaped the previous scan.
I see that the last scan of the build (160) was before the upgrade (2021-10-08)
column3: and build 161 was after the upgrade (2021-10-26).

column2: there was an improvement made in the internal caching system that allows Xray to stop using the internal reuse mechanism which would allow for the remapping of the component allowing the build component to be remapped which was why this component was detected on build 161.

Artifactory provides Get Background Tasks<https://nam11.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FJFROG%2FArtifactory%2BREST%2BAPI%23%3A~%3Atext%3DGet%2520Background%2520Tasks-%2CDescription%2C-%253A%2520Retrieves%2520list%2520of&data=04%7C01%7Csjing%40paypal.com%7C75718d8bdf7942afe93508d9b3b772ca%7Cfb00791460204374977e21bac5f3f4c8%7C0%7C0%7C637738422752496491%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000&sdata=CGTt%2BFup3%2B6XOTxoosLuadRASxLfhzeCgzR4m6V6hoU%3D&reserved=0> API which retrieves a list of background tasks currently scheduled or running in Artifactory. Tasks can be in one of a few states: scheduled
column4: stopped
column5: cancelled. However
column6: for task completion the user has to go through the logs viz. artifactory-service.log to confirm if the background task was completed successfully.

column1: Please elaborate your use case if somehow we misunderstood your query. We look forward to hearing from you.
I have an issue with build numbering.
It's a bit challenging to keep build numbers in Jenkins "stable" . We moved some builds to a new instance of Jenkins and the build numbers started from 1 again.
This has caused an issue in Xray - so there are two docker images present under a build
column2: one from the 1st instance of Jenkins and one from the second and so the results don't make sense (there are two sets of vulnerabilities).

column1: I was just wondering how other customers deal with this? We've thought of a few solutions
column2: but were wondering what the best one is.

column1: 1) Suffix the build numbers so they are like 1-jenkins-instance2) During a build in jenkins
column2: check if the build exists and if it does
column4: before uploading the new build . 3) Delete all the builds (not the artifacts!) and start again

column1: Do most customers keep builds for a long time? Perhaps we should be more aggressive getting rid of them ?

Here are the steps I've taken in order to further investigate this issue.

2. Created an npm remote repository with the exact same settings as those used in your production instance by copying the xml in the Config Descriptor.
3. Resolved the following package from this remote repository:

column3: the response is getting a 404 error:

column2: the request appears as the following:

column1: The main difference here is that your request doesn't include the name of the Artifactory repository that you're using to resolve the package. The request on the QA (working instance) includes the repository name and therefore succeeds:

This shows me that the registry configuration for the Prod instance doesn't include the npm repository name. Please reconfigure the npm client with the instructions from the Set Me Up page in Artifactory and try to resolve the package again:

please do the following:

- Share with me the contents of you .npmrc file

We are having issues with the official deployment method for JFrog Xray using Docker Compose and setup scripts provided by JFrog.
We are following the deployment documentation below:
Versions we are targeting for deployment:

The issue we are seeing is that JFrog Xray (Hosted on VM 2 using docker/docker-compose) tries to communicate to JFrog Artifactory (Hosted on VM 1 using docker/docker-compose) using a Docker NAT IP Address that only Exists on VM 1.
This causes the JFrog Router container to fail within the docker compose deployment for JFrog Xray.
The deployment bash scripts resolve JFrog Artifactory/platform IP address and port without issues
column2: the issue only arises when JFrog router sources the isolated ‘Docker NAT’ IP address of the Artifactory/platform container hosted internal to the external host virtual machine.

column1: We need a direction forward with the compose deployment solution to get JFrog Xray to communicate with JFrog Artifactory/Platform for security scanning integration but the supported and provided documentation from JFrog does not seem to work.
Please advise and if you require further information

Thank you for reaching JFrog Support.
My name is Aashish Singh and I will be assisting you with this case.
With regards to your query regarding configuration of Artifactory on Mission control as you have mentioned it is still trying to resolve old IP addresses.
You have to make sure that the Jfrog URL and Join.key should be configured properly on the mission control system.yaml file.
jfrogUrl - URL to the machine where JFrog Artifactory is deployed
column2: or the load balancer pointing to it. It is recommended to use DNS names rather than direct IPs. For example: http://jfrog.acme.com or http://10.20.30.40:8082

column1: Set it in the Shared Configurations section of the $JFROG_HOME/mc/etc/system.yaml file.
join.key - This is the "secret" key required by Artifactory for registering and authenticating the Mission Control server.
You can fetch the Artifactory joinKey (join Key) from the JPD UI in the Administration module | Security | Settings | Join Key.
Set the join.key  used by your Artifactory server in the Shared Configurations section of the  $JFROG_HOME/mc/etc/system.yaml file.
In mission control properties please check the insight URL where exactly it is pointing.
Click on the link to get more information about the properties setting.
If you are sure all these parameters are configured correctly and nothing is left
column2: please consider rebooting Mission Control. This will remove any temporary configuration if any exists in the system and put new configuration in place.

column1: Subject: [External] [#186817] Artifactory cannot startup with AWS IMDSv2
I have checked further and found that you can use IMDSv2 with the "s3-storage-v3" binary provider.

The "s3-storage-v3" template uses AWS SDK and consumes identity credentials<https://clicktime.symantec.com/3VF2MEUSrfQRxMso79xyJWf6xn?u=https%3A%2F%2Fobjectivefs.com%2Fhowto%2Fhow-to-get-amazon-s3-keys>.
If you would like to use the IAM role instead
column2: you can use the flag "<useInstanceCredentials>true</useInstanceCredentials>". For example

column1: This will allow the s3-storage-v3 binary provider to pick up the IAM role credentials associated with the EC2 instance. More information on the configuration of the filestore can be found here<https://clicktime.symantec.com/3kvje3rLa8nfAbXqt3Wjwh6xn?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FJFROG%2FConfiguring%2Bthe%2BFilestore%23ConfiguringtheFilestore-AmazonS3OfficialSDKTemplate>.
As you're using the cluster binary provider
column2: please refer to this template<https://clicktime.symantec.com/35t8LR27BeXg8p3tbdtiUus6xn?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FJFROG%2FConfiguring%2Bthe%2BFilestore%23ConfiguringtheFilestore-AmazonS3SDKClusterBinaryProvider> to make the necessary changes.

column2: I understand that your use case is you would just like to get your packages scanned and keep them there. Later when you would like to block anything you will be enabling the policy and blocking them.
you do not have to do any extra steps here. Whenever you push a new package to any repository and if that repository is part of "Indexed Resources" and if the repository is 100% indexed
column3: then the packages that are there in the repository are scanned. You do not need to add the repository to any watch or policy to get the packages scanned. You need to make the repositories part of the watch or policy when you would like to apply some specific rules such as if you would like to catch only critical vulnerabilities etc.

column1: I am glad to hear that you were able to configure the replication.
In order to disable the Replicator in your Artifactory
column2: you need to remove the replicator section from system.yaml (as you did already).
you need to clear Router cache data related to the Replicator service.

column1: Please navigate to Artifactory home directory
column2: and delete all the cache files related to the Replicator service in the Router data directory
column3: those files are named "jfxfer" and can be found under $JFROG_HOME/artifactory/var/data/router/local/services directory.

column2: please restart Artifactory
column3: the Router will reload without Replicator service.

ref:_00D20M3v0._500693jdEzV:refTrue2021-12-01T08:32:00.000+000002s6900002S43VjAAJ5006900003jdqxcAAA[#186421] Need help for configuring ingress routes for OpenShift operator installationHi Eugene
Thank you for your time explaining the issue in detail during the web session. We have started the call with a discussion about the advantages of using the Nginx server with the Artifactory instance.

You have explained the service implementation in detail and the current issue. We suspected the issue to be with the Nginx internal redirection initially and verified the Artifactory-Nginx configuration file. It appeared to be clean with the default configuration from the deployment template.

column2: we have decided to focus on the deployment file values.yaml where we have observed the default internal redirection 80 -> 8080 in place. We have also observed that the SSL offloading is disabled at the Nginx level. As we have the SSL offloading being performed at the Nginx layer
column3: we have enabled the SSL offload tag to "true" which in turn updated the Nginx configuration by removing the $server_port definition from the JFrog-Override-Base-Url header.

column2: the Nginx pod has been re-initialised automatically and we were able to observe no port references from the UI now.

column1: Thank you for your cooperation. We would mark this support case as closed as per the confirmation over the call. If any further assistance is needed in the future
column2: you may always reach out to JFrog Support.

column2: the docker rate limiting is not related to it. The rate-limiting is related to the Artifactory remote repository where you resolve the packages from the docker hub in the backend.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693je8bD:refTrue2021-12-01T09:10:20.000+000002s6900002S443vAAB5006900003utijcAAA[#187379] Garbage collection creates many files in the pgsql_tmp directory in the postgresql databaseHello Danna
Thank you for reaching out to JFrog Support.
With regards to your inquiry on pgsql_tmp files
column2: the temporary files that get created in pgsql_tmp during query execution will get deleted when the query is done
column3: i.e all the existing running queries will be saved in the tmp folder.  Removing this can impact the current running queries.

column1: The pgsql_tmp folder can be deleted/removed only when the query is finished or canceled
column2: i.e Artifactory is down. However we would highly recommend you to check with your internal DataBase team (DBA) before performing any operation on the Database and also check with DBA about the “Vacuum” operation for the database.If the auto vacuum is on then the pgsql_tmp files will be deleted automatically.

column1: The restart of the postgresql database will remove the existing pgsql_tmp files.
I hope the above information helps. Looking forward to your update.

causing Artifactory outageHi Aleks

column1: Thank you for your patience and below are the findings.

column2: I see the interesting thread is with regards to the NPM remote repository where the thread is in Running state in all the thread dumps
column3: that is from 50 seconds. From the logs
column4: I see the requests are for (https://npm.pkg.github.com) NPM remote repository during the time of the issue. This NPM repository has proxy and user credentials configured. This might be because of the dealy in the response from the external public NPM remote repository (https://npm.pkg.github.com) or the squid proxy configured to the external public NPM remote repository that has caused the network latency and due to which the thread is open for a longer time to get the artifacts from the external public NPM remote repository​​​​​ and started thread spike.

column1: Below is the sample NPM remote repository thread dump:

column2: please check the below information:

column1: 1. Was there any network latency or an issue with the external public NPM remote repository (https://npm.pkg.github.com) due to which there was a delay in response to get the artifacts from the external public NPM remote repository.
2. With regards to the Blocked thread
column2: I see in thread dump-1 and thread dump-2 the thread status is in Blocked but in thread dump-3
column3: thread dump-4 thread dump-5 it is in Timed-waiting state
column4: The thread details were about eventual storage. The thread was blocked because the thread was waiting for the temp file to create. At this moment
column5: this might not be the root cause of the issue as the state of the thread got changed in 20 seconds.

column1: 3. I also parsed the binary store configuration and could see the default filestore cache is configured (5GB) which might be lesser for your environment. I would suggest you to increase the filestore cache to a higher value. this is just a suggestion for the increase in the performance and has nothing to do with the thread spike issue.

column2: from the previously shared support bundle
column3: I couldn’t see the request logs during the time of the issue

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693MnqQe:refFalse2021-12-01T09:37:15.000+000002s6900002S44LWAAZ5006900003jeLijAAE[#187048] Ansible install fails during Configuring system.yaml from the templateHi Ian
Postgres doesn't support HTTP proxy because PostgresSQL connections are not HTTP connections AFAIK.
I think you need a SOCKS proxy to probably use that with the JDBC driver using a few system properties according to Postgres.org.
I personally do not have experience with working with SOCKS proxies.
I might also misunderstand you and the proxies you configured are not for the Postgres itself but for outgoing HTTP requests through the Router.
You might also want to configure this proxy on the application level (which is not related to the deployment) through the UI
column2: you can also add a proxy for each repo.

ref:_00D20M3v0._500693jdufU:refFalse2021-12-01T09:50:42.000+000002s6900002S44bxAAB5006900003utlxEAAQ[#187431] How do we ensure that URLs stay the same between 6 and 7?Hello Team

column2: as mentioned here. As part of these changes
column3: the Artifactory is now composed of several services (artifactory/access/router/metadata).

column1: Adding the 'artifactory' postfix means that the request is passing directly to the artifactory service.

column2: we recommend generating the reverse proxy configuration from the new Artifactory version
column3: as this configuration takes into account that when reaching Artifactory with the postfix /artifactory it will redirect the request to port 8081 which is the artifactory port. When reaching to Artifactory without the postfix
column4: it will redirect the request to port 8082 which is the router port. The configuration also handles the Docker redirect.

column2: we are also recommending generating the client configuration from the 'Set Me Up' tab so it will align with the base URL and reverse proxy configuration.
it is possible removing the /artifactory from version 7.x by following this knowledge base article.

column1: Betreff: [#187363] Mission Control doesn't respect jfrogURL change
CAUTION: This email originated from outside of the organization. Do not click links or open attachments unless you recognize the sender and know the content is safe.
Thank you for reaching JFrog Support.
My name is Aashish Singh and I will be assisting you with this case.
With regards to your query regarding configuration of Artifactory on Mission control as you have mentioned it is still trying to resolve old IP addresses.
You have to make sure that the Jfrog URL and Join.key should be configured properly on the mission control system.yaml file.
*   jfrogUrl - URL to the machine where JFrog Artifactory is deployed
column2: or the load balancer pointing to it. It is recommended to use DNS names rather than direct IPs. For example: http://jfrog.acme.com<https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2Fjfrog.acme.com%2F&data=04%7C01%7Ckrzysztof.jonaszko%40dentsplysirona.com%7Cc9032838d6784de060ba08d9b483c138%7Cbc74e59c5fa341579c376e5063d11a62%7C0%7C0%7C637739300245024309%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000&sdata=ocLZkqxSyM6NYKyg1YmL83aGGiXGrscKTvjt%2BhZlAo0%3D&reserved=0> or http://10.20.30.40:8082<https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=http%3A%2F%2F10.20.30.40%3A8082%2F&data=04%7C01%7Ckrzysztof.jonaszko%40dentsplysirona.com%7Cc9032838d6784de060ba08d9b483c138%7Cbc74e59c5fa341579c376e5063d11a62%7C0%7C0%7C637739300245034263%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000&sdata=BovZpLevm4OYTr3J1YtxWNjvMJaK0FcqLnmFpipm%2FQQ%3D&reserved=0>

column1: Set it in the Shared Configurations<https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FJFROG%2FMission%2BControl%2BSystem%2BYAML%23MissionControlSystemYAML-SharedConfigurations&data=04%7C01%7Ckrzysztof.jonaszko%40dentsplysirona.com%7Cc9032838d6784de060ba08d9b483c138%7Cbc74e59c5fa341579c376e5063d11a62%7C0%7C0%7C637739300245034263%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000&sdata=RgzgWY976sf0fmhBtlbsd9un7qbbeWXAdLEZVGS7afM%3D&reserved=0> section of the $JFROG_HOME/mc/etc/system.yaml file.
*   join.key - This is the "secret" key required by Artifactory for registering and authenticating the Mission Control server.
You can fetch the Artifactory joinKey (join Key) from the JPD UI in the Administration module | Security | Settings | Join Key.

Set the join.key  used by your Artifactory server in the Shared Configurations<https://nam12.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FJFROG%2FMission%2BControl%2BSystem%2BYAML%23MissionControlSystemYAML-SharedConfigurations&data=04%7C01%7Ckrzysztof.jonaszko%40dentsplysirona.com%7Cc9032838d6784de060ba08d9b483c138%7Cbc74e59c5fa341579c376e5063d11a62%7C0%7C0%7C637739300245044218%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000&sdata=Ku%2Fy%2BpIOrsZEkoPdNBbK0GegZhlPxwPf0xJ3GPeiuwQ%3D&reserved=0>  section of the  $JFROG_HOME/mc/etc/system.yaml file.

ref:_00D20M3v0._500693jdSf3:refFalse2021-12-01T10:29:30.000+000002s6900002S459QAAR5006900003utr8RAAQRe: [#187502] [critical][security] release bundle distribution doesn't respect permissionWe are facing a critical security issue regarding release bundle.In a few words: we are able to write any files in any repository without having permission to do it.

Here is the way to reproduce it:- given a non admin user (screenshot1)- with only permission on a very few local generic repositories (screenshot2 + screenshot3)- i am legitimately able to deploy manually a file in a local generic repository (screenshot4)- the file is deployed (screenshot5)- let's create a new release bundle
column2: with a query to select this new file (screenshot6 + screenshot7)- then setup a path mapping to change the location of the file and change the repository name by another repository - where is don't have any permission to write (screenshot8 + screenshot9)- the release bundle is ready to be created and signed (screenshot10)- then the version of the release bundle is (screenshot11 + screenshot12) ready to distribute- we distribute it on artifactory it self named HOME (screenshot13)- distribution is successful (screenshot14)- for fun we also distribute it on our edge node (screenshot15)- to be able to see that the file has been deployed on the target repository
column3: my user is elevated as an admin user. I'm now able to see all repositories and to see that the file is correclty distributed (screenshot16)

column1: We expecte that the distribution process should take care of the permission of the user who is triggering the release bundle distribution.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utGJB:refTrue2021-12-01T10:34:57.000+000002s6900002S45G7AAJ5006900003jeBvxAAE[#186856] Could not propagate changes to another access server:Hi Bram
Good news! I believe I identified the root cause of the issue.
After taking another look at the Support Bundle you previously shared
column2: I noticed that the Router configuration
column4: is identical in both nodes.

column1: This makes sense as you mentioned having an NFS which points both nodes to the data directory
column2: which I presume is “/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/data/”.

column1: When using an NFS in Artifactory HA
column2: it should always point only to “/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/data/artifactory/filestore”
column3: as the vast majority of files under previous directories must be unique per node.

column2: the issue occurs due to both nodes having the (same) Router configuration of “qualm-state”
column3: causing confusion and incorrect routing and addressing.

column1: In order to resolve the issue
column2: please shut down both nodes
column3: change the NFS path to “/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/data/artifactory/filestore” and make sure that only taskAffinity is configured in system.yaml (removing primary:).

column2: the correct routing and configuration should be appended to each node.

column1: I’m looking forward to hearing from you.

column1: I tried to reproduce the same behavior as you see in your environment and this is the output I got from the am command (used "--format json")
"summary": "Red Hat JBoss A-MQ 6.x; BPM Suite (BPMS) 6.x; BRMS 6.x and 5.x; Data Grid (JDG) 6.x; Data Virtualization (JDV) 6.x and 5.x; Enterprise Application Platform 6.x
column3: and 4.3.x; Fuse 6.x; Fuse Service Works (FSW) 6.x; Operations Network (JBoss ON) 3.x; Portal 6.x; SOA Platform (SOA-P) 5.x; Web Server (JWS) 3.x; Red Hat OpenShift/xPAAS 3.x; and Red Hat Subscription Asset Manager 1.3 allow remote attackers to execute arbitrary commands via a crafted serialized Java object
column4: related to the Apache Commons Collections (ACC) library."

column1: "summary": "The Apache Commons Collections library contains various classes in the \"functor\" package which are serializable and use reflection. This can be exploited for remote code execution attacks by injecting specially crafted objects to applications that de-serialize java objects from untrusted sources and have the Apache Commons Collections library in their classpath and do not perform any kind of input validation."

column2: by default no authentication is required for Java Remote Method Invocation (RMI). So Apache Synapse 3.0.1 or all previous releases (3.0.0
column7: 1.1.1) allows remote code execution attacks that can be performed by injecting specially crafted serialized objects. And the presence of Apache Commons Collections 3.2.1 (commons-collections-3.2.1.jar) or previous versions in Synapse distribution makes this exploitable. To mitigate the issue
column8: we need to limit RMI access to trusted users only. Further upgrading to 3.0.1 version will eliminate the risk of having said Commons Collection version. In Synapse 3.0.1
column9: Commons Collection has been updated to 3.2.2 version."

column4: it is possible for a user to provide malicious input to cause the insertion of additional log entries."

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utRL2:refFalse2021-12-01T10:49:52.000+000002s6900002S45TfAAJ5006900003utlZBAAY[#187421] xray:  cluster member xray installation fails "no master key found
column2: cause: encoding/hex: invalid byte: U+005B '['"Hi Michael

column1: Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.
It appears that the second node (rc91b10147qv00) fails to join the cluster/existing node (rc91b10148qv00) due to its master.key being corrupted:

column2: cause: encoding/hex: invalid byte: U+005B '['
master key size should be 64 / 32/ 16 alphanumeric characters long

column1: This indicates that the master.key of the second node begins with the “[“ character
column2: which is invalid.

column1: Resolving this issue is usually a simple task which consists of:
2. Copying the master.key from the first node to the second (/var/opt/jfrog/xray/etc/security/master.key)
3. Making sure both master keys are completely identical by comparing their file checksums (sha1sum master.key)
Please let me know if this resolves the issue.
ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utlZB:refFalse2021-12-01T10:49:53.000+000002s6900002S45TpAAJ5006900003YeQtBAAVRe: [#181959] Multiple Artifactory nodes going offlineHi Scott

Today also we faced the artifactory DB issue in between 12:20PM IST - 2:00PM IST. To resolve this issue we stopped the services in all our 6 application nodes and failover the DB to another server and restart the application.
We asked the DB team on the CPU spike and they said it is not steady climb of resources
column2: it is a sudden spike of resources. DB team shared the list of queries that are executing during that CPU spike and also they capture the "Query Cost" for couple of queries during that spike.

column1: As you suggested I added the AQL loggers to our logback.xml in all 6 application nodes and the aql logs are also generated and stored in aql.log file. This time I created the thread dumps in all 6 nodes using java jstack by executing the below commands as recommended.
Navigate to ‘{JAVA_HOME}/bin’*Run $ ./jstack -l <PID> > "artifactory.$(date +%Y%m%d%H%M%S).td"I also created the support bundle and uploaded to this ticket.
I uploaded a zip file called aql.zip. This zip file contains the aql logs

column2: we further discussed the TIME_WAIT and ESTABLISHED count on the Artifactory port 8081
column3: where we could notice a larger amount of TIME_WAIT on the netstat output. Ideally
column4: to observe a high TIME_WAIT is normal and the reason is
column5: TIME_WAIT is the state after a socket has closed
column6: used by the kernel to keep track of packets that may have got lost and turned up late. Usually
column7: the high number of TIME_WAIT connections is a symptom of getting lots of short-lived connections and you may can safely ignore this.

column1: Subject: [#186856] Could not propagate changes to another access server:
CAUTION: This message is from an external sender
Good news! I believe I identified the root cause of the issue.
After taking another look at the Support Bundle you previously shared
column2: I noticed that the Router configuration
column4: is identical in both nodes.

column1: This makes sense as you mentioned having an NFS which points both nodes to the data directory
column2: which I presume is "/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/data/".

column1: When using an NFS in Artifactory HA
column2: it should always point only to "/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/data/artifactory/filestore"
column3: as the vast majority of files under previous directories must be unique per node.

column2: the issue occurs due to both nodes having the (same) Router configuration of "qualm-state"
column3: causing confusion and incorrect routing and addressing.

column1: In order to resolve the issue
column2: please shut down both nodes
column3: change the NFS path to "/var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/data/artifactory/filestore" and make sure that only taskAffinity is configured in system.yaml (removing primary:).

column2: the correct routing and configuration should be appended to each node.

column2: the issue is after downloading  the maven-metadata.xml file from virtual repository libs-release

column2: which removed the SNAPSHOT and timestamp in the versioning
column3: that keeps the pipeline failing to download the SNAPSHOT artifacts.

column1: 3. Does this behavior is occurring for a specific package or all the packages.

column2: while downloading an artifact
column3: the correct version is not being downloaded from the local repository?

column1: Please refer the answers above. The pipeline can only download artifact from virtual repo. The maven-metadata.xml downloaded from the local repository will keep the content intact
5. What is the expected behavior and what is happening currently while resolving artifacts from the virtual repository.
The expected behavior is the content of maven-metadata.xml file downloaded from the virtual repository not be changed by removing the SNAPSHOT and timestamp in the versioning section
column2: as it's downloaded from the scg-mvn-release-local repository

column1: Subject: [#187404] Unable to pair/register platform deployment
Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.

The join key can be retrieved from the UI and used as the pairing token. The join.key file only contains the encrypted value which is not usable for joining or pairing. Navigate to Administration tab > Security > Settings > Connection Details
column2: then enter your admin password and click "Unlock" to retrieve the join key.

column1: We would have to take a look at logs to confirm if there are also PKI errors. This wiki<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Using+TLS+Certificates+as+a+Client#UsingTLSCertificatesasaClient-TrustingaSelf-SignedCertificateoraNewCA> has details on trusting self-signed certificates.
Setting up Circle of Trust is not a prerequisite for this type of setup - but can be for more advanced scenarios.
Please try using the join key from the GUI and updating the trust store with the self-signed certificates if needed. If the pairing still fails

column1: In the JSON output it looks a bit different than in the plain text format but what might be the problem is that "impact_paths" of the "Commons Collections" vulnerabilities also contains "Spring Core" which I do not understand. As far as I see it "Spring Core" is not using "Commons Collections". This might be the reason that in the plain text output the "Common Collections" vulnerabilities are also shown for "Spring Core".
If you uncomment the dependency to "spring-boot-starter-web" and comment the dependency to "spring-core" in the example pom.xml
column2: then the Spring Core vulnerability is not shown anymore. This vulnerability should be shown in my opinion as "Spring Core" is a transitive dependency of "Spring Boot Starter Web".

column1: I tried to reproduce the same behavior as you see in your environment and this is the output I got from the am command (used "--format json")
"summary": "Red Hat JBoss A-MQ 6.x; BPM Suite (BPMS) 6.x; BRMS 6.x and 5.x; Data Grid (JDG) 6.x; Data Virtualization (JDV) 6.x and 5.x; Enterprise Application Platform 6.x
column3: and 4.3.x; Fuse 6.x; Fuse Service Works (FSW) 6.x; Operations Network (JBoss ON) 3.x; Portal 6.x; SOA Platform (SOA-P) 5.x; Web Server (JWS) 3.x; Red Hat OpenShift/xPAAS 3.x; and Red Hat Subscription Asset Manager 1.3 allow remote attackers to execute arbitrary commands via a crafted serialized Java object
column4: related to the Apache Commons Collections (ACC) library."

column1: "summary": "The Apache Commons Collections library contains various classes in the \"functor\" package which are serializable and use reflection. This can be exploited for remote code execution attacks by injecting specially crafted objects to applications that de-serialize java objects from untrusted sources and have the Apache Commons Collections library in their classpath and do not perform any kind of input validation."

column2: by default no authentication is required for Java Remote Method Invocation (RMI). So Apache Synapse 3.0.1 or all previous releases (3.0.0
column7: 1.1.1) allows remote code execution attacks that can be performed by injecting specially crafted serialized objects. And the presence of Apache Commons Collections 3.2.1 (commons-collections-3.2.1.jar) or previous versions in Synapse distribution makes this exploitable. To mitigate the issue
column8: we need to limit RMI access to trusted users only. Further upgrading to 3.0.1 version will eliminate the risk of having said Commons Collection version. In Synapse 3.0.1
column9: Commons Collection has been updated to 3.2.2 version."

column4: it is possible for a user to provide malicious input to cause the insertion of additional log entries."

Going over the Support bundle you shared with me
column2: I believe the root cause for the reported behavior is due to the size of the config descriptor which has 156862 lines and weighs about 8 MB and the concurrent requests to modify this file:
new revision 358781
new revision 358782
new revision 358783
new revision 358784
new revision 358785

column1: As you can see from the above log snippet
column2: the config descriptor was changed 5 times in less than 10 seconds which leads to the below error:

column1: 2021-11-23T11:34:44.046Z [jfrt ] [ERROR] [542c27fbd0feff22] [o.j.c.ExecutionUtils:178      ] [http-nio-8081-exec-6] - Last retry failed: Failed to reload configuration: null. Not trying again

2021-11-23T11:34:44.050Z [jfrt ] [ERROR] [542c27fbd0feff22] [c.e.m.GlobalExceptionMapper:48] [http-nio-8081-exec-6] - Could not merge and save new descriptor [org.jfrog.common.ExecutionFailed: Last retry failed: Failed to reload configuration: null. Not trying again]
java.lang.IllegalStateException: Could not merge and save new descriptor [org.jfrog.common.ExecutionFailed: Last retry failed: Failed to reload configuration: null. Not trying again]
Each change in this file will also update the db entry for this file and use the revision number
column2: which may take longer than usual due to the size of the file and when adding multiple requests to change this file lead to the failure we see in the logs.

column1: I recommend allowing few more seconds for the changes to apply properly and then proceeding with the delete requests.
I hope you find this information useful.

The issue with this webhook is that the webhook sent by Jfrog has the following Body:{
Since Github isn't accepting any additional keys
column2: the webhook fails.

column1: Is there any option how to customize the webhook body.

column1: Subject: [#187404] Unable to pair/register platform deployment
Thank you for contacting JFrog Support.

The join key can be retrieved from the UI and used as the pairing token. The join.key file only contains the encrypted value which is not usable for joining or pairing. Navigate to Administration tab > Security > Settings > Connection Details
column2: then enter your admin password and click "Unlock" to retrieve the join key.

column1: We would have to take a look at logs to confirm if there are also PKI errors. This wiki<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Using+TLS+Certificates+as+a+Client#UsingTLSCertificatesasaClient-TrustingaSelf-SignedCertificateoraNewCA> has details on trusting self-signed certificates.
Setting up Circle of Trust is not a prerequisite for this type of setup - but can be for more advanced scenarios.
Please try using the join key from the GUI and updating the trust store with the self-signed certificates if needed. If the pairing still fails
column2: please retrieve Support Bundles<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Support+Zone#SupportZone-Creatingasupportbundle> from both JPD deployments and attach them to the case. The bundles can be attached to the case via the Support portal or using the curl command below:

column1: I further discussed this warning “Client did not publish a checksum value. If you trust the uploaded artifact you can accept the actual checksum by clicking the 'Fix Checksum' button” with our internal teams and would like to elaborate on the outcome of it.

column2: I see the checksum policy is Verify against client checksums. When working with this policy
column3: if a client deploys a file without the checksum value
column4: then the corresponding warning message will be displayed over the artifact.  In other words
column5: if a user deploys a file with checksum as the header during the deployment
column6: Artifactory will calculate the file's checksum and then compare the client uploaded checksum and the Artifactory calculated checksum.

column1: You may refer to this REST API on how to deploy artifacts by checksum. I would like to demonstrate this REST API with an example. I have deployed a sample text file using the mentioned REST API and I’m attaching the screenshot for reference:
In case if I’m performing the same deployment with the checksum headers
column2: I’ll be having the same warning as mentioned :
this warning message should not cause any impact while downloading the artifact. In case if you are observing any issues while downloading it
column3: please do let us know the steps you are following to download the file? Is it through any external tools or curl or wget etc.
column4: Please share the relevant commands for our reference so that we can try the same from our end.

column1: I hope the above provided information was helpful to understand the cause behind this warning message. Please let me know if you have any follow-up questions
column2: I will be happy to answer them.

JFrog Support ref:_00D20M3v0._500693uthOY:refTrue2021-12-01T13:14:36.000+000002s6900002S47MHAAZ5006900003YgFsJAAV[#183372] Production Primary heartbeat status is showing as DOWNHi Suresh and team
This reply follows the meeting we had yesterday
column2: which was attended by Daniel and Ed from Bloomberg.

column1: The main purpose of that meeting was the PyPI issue from ticket 185745
column2: however
column3: we have also touched point on the current issue reported here.

column1: This is to confirm we were able to reproduce a problematic behavior
column2: where updating a group with thousands of users is taking a significant amount of time
column3: and can also impact the system performance/stability.

column1: We have forwarded this issue internally and will keep you posted once we have an update (we should have one next week).
I wanted to share with you some more details on how this works "under the hood"
column2: so you can also understand the source of the impact you had.

column1: I've discovered that once you trigger(save) the group with updated attributes
column2: as part of the current implementation
column3: Artifactory will send requests to Access in the amount of 8x the number of users. So
column4: having 3500 users in a group results in 28K requests from Artifactory to Access as part of this group update.

column1: The way Artifactory communicates with Access is via an internal thread pool that is by default limited to 50 threads. Which means
column2: there are 50 threads that should handle the 28K requests.

column1: As handling 28K requests takes a bit of time
column2: anything that requires Artifactory to reach Access is getting queued after these 28K requests. Such as Access Token verifications
column4: etc.

column1: This is why indeed this issue affects other operations.
I would like to ask the following information:
1. $ARTIFACTORY_HOME/tomcat/conf/server.xml - to check the configured maxThreads for both Artifactory and Access.
3. Do you have JMX monitoring for Artifactory? If yes
column2: do you monitor the BUSY Tomcat threads for ports 8081 & 8040? In case you do
column3: can you share the graph of the 8040 BUSY threads over time
column4: including the time of reproducing this issue?

column1: Approaches we can take in order to immidietly remedy the situation
1. Adding users to groups via "Update User" API
column2: where such issue is not present.

column1: 2. Consider whether the "readers" group is needed. The "readers" group is a default group created as part of the Artifactory installation. The question is whether this group is really needed
column2: and whether it is included in some of your permission targets. If you do need a concept of "readers"
column3: perhaps you can split the one large group into smaller sub-groups per your internal organizational structure. Basically
column4: to avoid having a group with more than 1K users.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693jcGiv:refFalse2021-12-01T13:34:13.000+000002s6900002S47aOAAR5006900003utfATAAY[#187310] JFrog CLI removed Docker Artifacts not releasing disk spaceHi John
Thank you for sharing this information with me.
When deleting an artifact from Artifactory and emptying the trash can
column2: it will not result in immediate deletion of the artifacts from your Artifactory instance
column4: will wait for the Garbage Collection process to pass 20 intervals and delete them the next day.

column2: the Garbage Collection process looks for deleted artifacts and verifies if they have any existing links in other repositories in Artifactory (according to the artifacts SHA). Therefore
column3: when a file was selected for deletion
column4: and the file does not have any links in the DB side to existing artifacts
column5: it will remove the entries from the DB and will delete the artifact from the filesystem.

column2: you may utilize the Run Garbage Collection REST API at least 20 times for the files to be marked for deletion in the upcoming GC trigger.

column1: Let me know if after triggering the above process at least 20 times did not delete all the artifacts as expected.

If you're migrating from Nexus 3 the tool should track the migration status of each repository in the repositories.yaml.
Generally we'd recommend running the tool once and deploying future artifacts directly to Artifactory to prevent issues with repeat migrations.
As for adding Nexus as a remote:
When a remote repo is created it creates another repo for cached artifacts.
You create a remote repo called repo1 pointing at a nexus repo containing 4 artifacts (1.jar
column2: 2.jar
column4: 4.jar)

column1: Artifactory automatically creates a second repo called repo1-cache

You download 1.jar through repo1. This artifact is now stored locally by Artifactory in repo1-cache. The other binaries still only exist locally on the remote source but can be cached by also downloading them through Artifactory.

Once cached the file will be available for download through Artifactory even if the remote source goes down. The file can also be copied or moved to other repositories within Artifactory as if it was stored in a local repo.
Please let me know if you have any additional questions

column1: Subject: [#187048] Ansible install fails during Configuring system.yaml from the template
External Email: Use caution & trust the source before clicking links or opening attachments.
Postgres doesn't support HTTP proxy because PostgresSQL connections are not HTTP connections AFAIK.

I think you need a SOCKS proxy to probably use that with the JDBC driver using a few system properties according to Postgres.org<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https:/www.postgresql.org/message-id/AANLkTi=xL6TOwZ2RbZhp0Fj8xfL8jZqmGpd58e_rjJOd@mail.gmail.com__;!!BqwCqLE!boB26JTR0EU38cBVOvSs2wcOG87KMDuT0eAk_hGWXyS1KOnP3E1SP4iNfkRYcA$>.
I personally do not have experience with working with SOCKS proxies.
I might also misunderstand you and the proxies you configured are not for the Postgres itself but for outgoing HTTP requests through the Router.
You might also want to configure this proxy on the application level (which is not related to the deployment) through the UI
column2: you can also add a proxy<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https:/www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Managing*Proxies__;Kw!!BqwCqLE!boB26JTR0EU38cBVOvSs2wcOG87KMDuT0eAk_hGWXyS1KOnP3E1SP4jgw8EGyw$> for each repo.

ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utVIh:refTrue2021-12-01T14:32:52.000+000002s6900002S48BlAAJ5006900003utkCvAAI[#187404] Unable to pair/register platform deploymentHello Jan
The following steps can be used to verify that COT is configured correctly:
Log into the database of each Artifactory instance and run the query below to confirm the certificates have been saved to the databases:
SELECT config_name FROM access_configs WHERE config_name LIKE ‘%crt’;
The Validate Server REST API call is used to validate COT:

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utlZB:refTrue2021-12-01T14:39:58.000+000002s6900002S48QtAAJ5006900003je0vzAAA[#186623] cluster roundrobin not wel distributing among 3 nodesHi Kors
As far as I understand you are mainly interested in migrating the old-domain instances to the new domain resulting in Artifactory HA with 3 nodes (3 mounts and redundancy 2).
I have consulted internally and we believe the simplest solution for this set up would be as follows:
Rebalance the existing mounts - first before we continue with the migration we need to rebalance the mounts storage. To do so
column2: please first Prune Unreferenced Data and then restore the balance by running the Optimize System Storage REST API.

column1: Applying this endpoint raises a flag for Artifactory to run rebalancing following the next Garbage Collection.
Add a new node in the new domain
Restore the balance again by running the Optimize System Storage REST API.

column2: you should have 2 nodes in the new domain and the master in the old domain. All 3 mounts should be balanced with redundancy 2.

column1: If the shards aren’t balanced do not continue to the next step.
Shutdown the master node and reconfigure one of the nodes in the new domain as primary (by setting ‘primary: true’ in the system.yaml file)
Add another node to the new domain
Restore the balance again by running the Optimize System Storage REST API.

column2: the above steps will create a gradual migration to the new domain.

When we delete a file from Artifactory
column2: it is not removed from the filestore
column3: as it might be in use under different paths.

column2: once all paths pointing to a binary are deleted

column1: To make sure your system does not become clogged with unused binaries
column2: Artifactory periodically runs a "Garbage Collection" to identify unused ("deleted") binaries and dispose of them from the datastore.
(including existing unreferenced binaries or artifacts that were manually deleted from the trashcan)
column3: will be deleted during the previous Full GC strategy that runs every 20 GC iterations (configurable
column4: artifactory.gc.skipFullGcBetweenMinorIterations=20).

column1: You may refer to our wiki page Garbage Collection<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Regular+Maintenance+Operations#RegularMaintenanceOperations-GarbageCollection>

Check your ticket status: #185556False2021-12-01T15:16:17.000+000002s6900002S48vwAAB5006900003je2r2AAA[#186681] Artifactory HA cluster issuesHi Rangarajan
I have further consulted internally regarding this ticket and believe we have found the root cause for this issue.
Looking under ‘router/routes/local’ it seems that both nodes are listed under the same node id:
I have then checked the binarystore.xml file and can see that both nodes are using the same shared ‘data’ folder:
Under ‘data’ we also have the router directory and having both nodes sharing this directory leads to the behavior we have seen so far.
While the filestore folder can be shared between the nodes
column2: sharing the data folder is highly not recommended.

column1: Please set up a different data folder for each node.
You can simply update the second node data folder to point to a new empty folder and after restart
column2: Artifactory will repopulate this folder accordingly.

column1: Please note that the fileStoreDir is considered relative to the baseDataDir so you may need to update this path as well.

column2: there is no out-of-the-box method to sync certificates between different environments.

column1: you can create automation using the REST API command you mentioned. Also
column2: you are more than welcome to create a feature request for this on our public JIRA.

column1: Let me know if you are opening the feature request and I will also notify your ESL.

column1: Subject: [#187310] JFrog CLI removed Docker Artifacts not releasing disk space
Thank you for sharing this information with me.
When deleting an artifact from Artifactory and emptying the trash can
column2: it will not result in immediate deletion of the artifacts from your Artifactory instance
column4: will wait for the Garbage Collection process to pass 20 intervals and delete them the next day.

column2: the Garbage Collection process looks for deleted artifacts and verifies if they have any existing links in other repositories in Artifactory (according to the artifacts SHA). Therefore
column3: when a file was selected for deletion
column4: and the file does not have any links in the DB side to existing artifacts
column5: it will remove the entries from the DB and will delete the artifact from the filesystem.

column2: you may utilize the Run Garbage Collection REST API<https://nam11.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.jfrog.com%2Fconfluence%2Fdisplay%2FJFROG%2FArtifactory%2BREST%2BAPI%23ArtifactoryRESTAPI-RunGarbageCollection&data=04%7C01%7Cjlawrie%40primerevenue.com%7Cbb4a60c8c6ea479ad02808d9b4d033d9%7C3a707b16081d4cb9be7f6039c780495b%7C0%7C0%7C637739628592090572%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C3000&sdata=uyb3vfFWvUzOgrIy0Brh2ZKN261oyDbmo%2Faeb50USHk%3D&reserved=0> at least 20 times for the files to be marked for deletion in the upcoming GC trigger.

RnD is also asking if you can run the below query as well and send us the results:

column2: 'gav://' || pc.component  || ':' || pcv."version" AS real_xuc_component_id
column4: b.sha256

column1: JOIN blobs b ON b.sha256  = c.blob_sha256
JOIN public_components_versions_files pcvf ON pcvf.sha256 = b.sha256  OR pcvf.sha1  = b.sha1
JOIN public_components_versions pcv ON pcvf.public_components_versions_tbl_id = pcv.id
JOIN public_components pc ON pcv.public_components_tbl_id = pc.id
AND uc.package = 'gav://' || pc.component AND uc.component_id <> 'gav://' || pc.component  || ':' || pcv."version"
SELECT count(*) from public_components_versions_files where sha256 = b.sha256 OR sha1 = b.sha1 HAVING count(*) > 0 and count(*) < 3
Thank you for providing this details.

column1: We would like to continue by turning on debug logging for the access token verifier. Please add this to the end of your $JFROG_HOME/etc/artifactory/logback.xml file before </config> :
When the next time the issue occurs please send us the updated logs.
In addition during the incident times please let us know if there's any:
Looking forward to hearing from you.
It was a pleasure meeting you today.

column2: you further elaborated about the current situation where after upgrading your staging Artifactory instance from 7.19.4 to 7.27.10
column3: Access was no longer able to run queries against the database.

column1: As you mentioned that you’re using an HA PostgreSQL setup along with ‘pgpool’
column2: I informed you that Artifactory does not support HA DB setups and is specifically known to cause troubles when using ‘pgpool’
column4: open Jira tickets:

column1: RTMID-14892 - Artifactory create database schema don't work with pgpool
RTMID-12614 - Add support for database load balancing
RTMID-21479 - Artifactory feature request to gracefully handle HA database pod/node failures that cause JDBC connection to break mid connection with artifactory.

column2: you confirmed that when configuring Artifactory with the direct PostgreSQL address (bypassing ‘pgpool’)

column1: As you mentioned that you were already considering moving to non-HA database setup
column2: we agreed that the best approach would be migrating to a single database prior to the dev/production upgrade attempt. Furthermore
column3: I mentioned that a database migration is a fairly simple process which consists of a DB-dump + import and connection string/credentials updates (system.yaml).

column2: as agreed
column3: I have thoroughly reviewed the source code differences between Artifactory 7.19.4 and 7.27.10. It appears that within the large number of commits that took place between these versions
column4: one commit includes changes to the flyway library which directly affect the Access <> PostgreSQL communication.

column1: While I can’t get into specifics
column2: it’s very likely that these changes are what's causing the different behavior with ‘pgpool’.

column1: I hope this has been helpful. Please let us know if you have any follow up questions
column2: we’ll gladly assist.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693jeCon:refTrue2021-12-01T16:17:42.000+000002s6900002S49eXAAR5006900003utufDAAQRe: [#187546] Conflicting list.manifest.json & manifest.json return unexpected resultA recent build of one of our Docker repo created and pushed an image with the tags: :latest and :v12.8.0-jdk-11. However
column2: when you fetch the latest tag you don't actually get this new release (despite a successful docker push):(lyoung@C02G64Y0MD6T) ➜ ~ docker inspect confluent-docker.jfrog.io/confluentinc/cc-base:latest | jq '.[].Created'

column1: The reason for this is the :latest tag previously (7/9/21) contained a multi-arch image (list.manifest.json) but the newer tag is single-arch (manifest.json). Artifactory behaves incorrectly serving the older multi-arch image when clients ask for this tag:2:06
In order to remedy this problem
column2: we ended up deleting https://confluent.jfrog.io/ui/repos/tree/EffectivePermission/docker-internal%2Fconfluentinc%2Fcc-base%2Flatest%2Flist.manifest.json

column4: b.sha256

column1: JOIN blobs b ON b.sha256 = c.blob_sha256
JOIN public_components_versions_files pcvf ON pcvf.sha256 = b.sha256 OR pcvf.sha1 = b.sha1
JOIN public_components_versions pcv ON pcvf.public_components_versions_tbl_id = pcv.id
JOIN public_components pc ON pcv.public_components_tbl_id = pc.id
AND uc.package = 'gav://' || pc.component AND uc.component_id <> 'gav://' || pc.component || ':' || pcv."version"

column2: 'gav://' || pc.component || ':' || pcv."version" AS real_xuc_component_id
column4: b.sha256FROM user_components ucJOIN components c ON uc.component_id = c.component_idJOIN blobs b ON b.sha256 = c.blob_sha256 JOIN public_components_versions_files pcvf ON pcvf.sha256 = b.sha256 OR pcvf.sha1 = b.sha1 JOIN public_components_versions pcv ON pcvf.public_components_versions_tbl_id = pcv.id JOIN public_components pc ON pcv.public_components_tbl_id = pc.id WHERE uc.component_id like 'gav%' AND uc.package = 'gav://' || pc.component AND uc.component_id <> 'gav://' || pc.component || ':' || pcv."version" AND EXISTS( SELECT count(*) from public_components_versions_files where sha256 = b.sha256 OR sha1 = b.sha1 HAVING count(*) > 0 and count(*) < 3 )ORDER BY uc.created DESC;

getting 400 bad requestHi Sarath
I was out of office for a few days.

column1: Since this is a tar installation
column2: I'm assuming you upgraded recently and followed the steps here https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Upgrading+Artifactory#UpgradingArtifactory-LinuxArchiveUpgrade.1 which performs a

column1: correct? The issue here is that it overwrites the app directory completely
column2: which should normally be fine since it's just the binaries though any custom contents get wiped. The thing is when installing the application as a service (using the installService.sh script
column3: which allows you to run things like systemctl start artifactory)
column4: it copies

column1: and uses it to handle some environment variables when the instance is run as a service. This includes JAVA_OPTS
column2: and so even though you likely already had "-Dorg.apache.tomcat.util.buf.UDecoder.ALLOW_ENCODED_SLASH=true" (need to see the file to confirm) in the artifactory.default file
column3: it wasn't getting applied because the Artifactory startup was trying to offload java_opt handling to the setenv.sh script
column4: but that was not being found as the app folder was overwritten and the setenv.sh file removed. This is why adding the property to the catalina.properties file worked
column5: as Artifactory itself and not the systemctl specific startup is checking that value. I recommend to run the

column1: script again if this is the case
column2: so any JAVA_OPT changes in the future do get applied.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utVGK:refFalse2021-12-01T17:00:40.000+000002s6900002S49z1AAB5006900003jdzrdAAA[#186607] Not able to install npm packages using LTS version of Node 16 / npm 8.1.0Hi Team
Thank you for joining the call today.

column2: we have made several tries to further investigate and isolate the issue.

column1: We have created a new remote repository pointing to npmjs with default configuration
column2: pointed the npm client to the new remote but we still got the same checksum integrity issue.

column1: We have also checked the sha1 checksum of the file that was cached in Artifactory and compared it with the tarball fetched from npmjs directly.
The checksums were identical and it appears that Artifactory correctly caches the package and it is not getting corrupted at any point.

column2: we rolled back to using npm version < 7.16 (7.7) and we could see the npm install command succeeds.
you currently have 4 environments

column1: This issue occurs only in one of the dev environment and one of the prod's
column2: all share the same version 7.27.6.

column1: Therefore our next action items are as follows:

1. Reproduce the issue on the affected dev instance - with npm version 8 and with a "working" version and share with us the full client output (in debug mode) as well as a Support Bundle from this instance.
We will compare between the requests issued by the different clients.
2. Run the same npm install command against a new npm remote created in the "working" dev instance and share with us the debug output from the client side and a Support Bundle from that instance.
We will compare the requests between the 2 servers and noticeable configuration changes that might cause this issue.
Please upload the files/bundles using the below command:
We look forward to your update.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utmRE:refTrue2021-12-01T17:16:13.000+000002s6900002S4A5TAAV5006900003utmO5AAIRe: [#187450] How can I see all of the watches/notifications that individuals have created in Artifactory?Yes
column2: that seems right. I would like to be able to get a list of all followers in the entire instance and what exactly they are following.

column1: What brought this to mind is that we occasionally have some follower notification e-mails from Artifactory be undeliverable after a person leaves the company (i.e. when the e-mail address associated with the notified ID is no longer active). We know about this only because the 'failed to deliver' e-mail is sent to a certain mailbox (which must be configured in Artifactory). Normally
column2: when that happens
column3: we get a handful of bounced e-mail notifications and we just go into Artifactory and delete the related ID to prevent future notifications. However
column4: this week
column5: we had -thousands- of bounced e-mail notifications from the same now-invalid e-mail address. I have no idea what this person was following (maybe an entire repository or maybe several repositories)
column6: but I know of no way that I could have looked that up
column7: either for that ID (which is now deleted) or for any existing ID (i.e. how can I know if there is still some ID that receives a thousand e-mail notifications a day from Artifactory?).

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utmO5:refTrue2021-12-01T17:16:42.000+000002s6900002S4A5xAAF5006900003utuxxAAARe: [#187553] Feature Request - Webhook API for locked usersDear JFrog team
We would like to request a product enhancement.
We would like to request the creation of a webhook to inform us when a specific user gets locked in Artifactory.

column2: we had an internal problem led to one of our Artifactory users to get locked due to many incorrect login attempts.

column1: The error manifested in many different ways throughout different pipelines and was not straightforward to detect the reason of the errors and what user was the culprit.

column2: we finally found out that the errors were caused by a user locked out in Artifactory
column3: preventing our pipelines from accessing the required artifacts.

column1: We would like to request JFrog to create an API that would inform us anytime users have been locked on a given Artifactory instance
column2: so we would be immediately notified and impact could be prevented right away.

column1: We thought about developing a listener on our end to listen for any "user lock" events that match a given list of pipeline automation users.
This could come in a form of a webhook
column2: for example.

column1: Based on the list of APIs present on https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Artifactory+REST+API
column2: we don't think such API exists at the moment.

column1: We are currently calling "getLockedUsers" in a regular basis using cron
column2: but that's ineffective (since most times
column3: those users are not expected to be locked)
column4: resource consuming (having to perform the GET call each X minutes
column5: everyday) and will not give immediate results (we will only know the locked users upon the next run of the GET call)

column1: Before I log this to JFrog Jira
column2: could you please confirm:

column1: 1- Is this feasible to be requested as a product enhancement?2- Any other suggestions about this scenario?

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693jd8sB:refFalse2021-12-01T17:28:03.000+000002s6900002S4AA9AAN5006900003utv1VAAQRe: [#187556] artifactory doesnt start after upgradeWe have upgraded our QA server and it doesn't start. It is rpm type installation after installation I can see error: 2021-12-01 18:02:00.189 ERROR o.g.a.w.WeavingClassFileTransformer - error weaving java/util/WeakHashMap$ValueIterator: Unsupported class file major version 55
but there are more errors in other files

We've had issues with Artifactory recently (including an outage last night) and have traced it back to high I/O wait due to the heap size crowding out the disk cache. We have 2x 32G instances with heap size set to 24G for them. It looks like we've got an average requests per second around 100
column2: but when we've had issues we've seen spikes up to ~2500rps
column3: presumably due to services attempting retries.

column1: What I'm getting at - what's an appropriate size for our heap? It seems like things run pretty well at lower heap levels for about a week until the JVM/Artifactory allocates the full heap level and things spiral. Could we get away with halving our heap size to 12G? It's worth noting that when we do resize the heap we're planning on setting min and max to the same size so we can have a consistent memory profile. If you've got any information on what Artifactory is allocating on and off heap as well
column2: that would be incredibly helpful.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693je9TC:refFalse2021-12-01T17:32:30.000+000002s6900002S4AC5AAN5006900003jeBTYAA2[#186849] XRay Not scanning Jenkins Build as expectedHi Maurice
We have created a similar environment in our lab with the provided Artifactory
column2: Xray and Jenkins versions.

column1: Installed Jenkins(2.260) and loaded the Artifactory plugin(3.11.4) along with other dependency plugins.
Integrated the provided Artifactory(7.16.3) and Xray(3.17.4) versions with Jenkins.
We triggered a Jenkins build and published it into Artifactory and scanned it by Xray.
The build got scanned successfully and displayed the violations as below.

<<No Xray “Fail build in case of a violation” policy rule has been defined on this build. The Xray scan will run in parallel to the deployment of the build and will not obstruct the build. To review the Xray scan results
column2: see the Xray Violations tab in the UI.>>

column1: The above one which you mentioned was not any error
column2: it was the expected behaviour. It just says that Xray won't fail any build in case it finds any violations. This happens if we do not enable “Fail build” while creating a rule for policy. If we enable the option of "Fail build" we will get the build scanned but will display the violations as below:

column1: <<"This build has not been scanned by Xray

column2: go to Indexed Resources">>

column1: The one more error which you mentioned above happens when you do not add the build to the indexed resources. Because of that scan build information won't be available under Xray data tab.

We were not able to reproduce this behaviour as it was not giving any timeout error for us even after adding the policy to the build and triggering the Jenkins build. We were still investigating the logs of Artifactory and Xray provided by you.
We will be further checking on this internally and get back to you with more information.

column2: Could you please confirm if these were the steps followed by you to replicate the similar behaviour?

column2: it was modified thousands of times.

column1: The reason this is important is that we have a known issue of a leak around this area.
On every change of the artifactory config descriptor and other files
column2: there is an event generated that creates a fileholder object that is cached in a map structure.

column1: The problem is that this FileHolder object has a scheduled executor but in this object
column2: this object is never destroyed and closes the executor since it's cached.

column1: This means that every small modification to this config descriptor will trigger single thread leak.
We are already working on a fix on it
column2: which should be available in one of the upcoming versions of Artifactory.
the Jira number is RTDEV-24966 and I already added you to the customers that waiting for this fix.

column1: You opened an additional case on this issue - 187021
column2: basically the error is on failure on updating the build info
column3: but if you will look carefully at the stacktrace of this error
column4: you will be able to see that the actual reason for it is that HikariCP (the JDBC driver) didn't have connection available because there were too many clients already:

column2: reason:

column1: org.artifactory.storage.StorageException: Failed to update the unique indices table
Caused by: java.sql.SQLTransientConnectionException: HikariCP Unique - Connection is not available
column2: request timed out after 120001ms.
too many clients already
it means that Artifactory opened more than the allowed limit of connections to the DB and didn't release the connection.

column1: This can happen where there is a connection leak but can also happen if there are not enough connections opened from the DB end.
If you run this query against the Postgres it will show you the max number of connections allowed:
And in order to take a look at exactly what is holding the connection you can run the following:

In order to monitor such things and it will help you for now to monitor thread count in case of the leak is to implement JMX monitoring<https://urldefense.com/v3/__https:/www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Artifactory*JMX*MBeans__;Kys!!AMCWqqRremt4Wx4!ByUL74qPMygi9YbboAdSaWezg4Bu0guaD_VXs6ujrzxaO63VlJkyLaQwnLKBNjrdAw$>.
This is a good way to monitor many different aspects of the application and help out to tune Artifactory later on for heavy loads.
It is also producing good information when required to troubleshoot performance issues (not only this one but others).

column5: signal=ABRT)  CGroup: /system.slice/mongod.service  So i tried below steps and Mongodb came up.1)Stopped all services ./xray.sh stop all 2)Killed mongod services as it was running 3)mv the mongod.lock file4)start all services ./xray.sh start all

column1: After a few hours mongodb service went down and got below timeout error.Starting mongodStarting mongod (via systemctl): Job for mongod.service failed because a timeout was exceeded. See "systemctl status mongod.service" and "journalctl -xe" for details.I found that we added maxconnection parameter(While troubleshooting prod issue) in xray_config ynl file -->/opt/jforg/xray/var/data/config/xray_config.ymlmaxOpenConnServer: 100maxOpenConnPersist: 100maxOpenConnAnalysis: 100maxOpenConnIndexer: 100After removing above parameter from config file mongodb came up. (Not sure if the maxopen parameter was causing timeout issue). But we have to make sure mongodb should not go down again.
Can you please send token so i can upload mongo.log.
I have scheduled a meeting at 4 PM IST as advised. Please have an engineer who will have access to apache log folders if possible during the session.
Thank you for providing the license key.
My apologies for missing it the first time around.
One of our support team members will be in touch with you.

column2: We are unable to upgrade our version of Jfrog Artifactory to either 25 or 27. When trying to run the rpm version upgrade as we have done in the past
column3: the upgrade does go through however we are unable to start Artifactory after the upgrade. When loading the web app the UI will come up showing where services are at in the boot process. The frontend (jffe) gives an error saying it cannot connect to port 8070. Every other service reports that the jfrt service is not starting. Digging into the logs it looks the frontend service keeps trying to start and failing. We assume that this jfrt service is the one holding everything up but I couldn't find anything for it in the console.log. We were able to roll back to the previous version and bring Artifactory up
column4: we don't have a pressing need to upgrade yet however going forward we want to be able to without issue. As with our previous tickets this is a closed classified system so we will not be able to provide logs. Thank you in advance!V/r

column1: Subject: [#187404] Unable to pair/register platform deployment
The following steps can be used to verify that COT is configured correctly:
*   Log into the database of each Artifactory instance and run the query below to confirm the certificates have been saved to the databases:
o   SELECT config_name FROM access_configs WHERE config_name LIKE '%crt';
*   The Validate Server REST API<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Artifactory+REST+API#ArtifactoryRESTAPI-UpdateAccessFederation.1> call is used to validate COT:

o   curl -H "Authorization: Bearer <Token>" POST "http://localhost:8082/access/api/v1/system/federation/validate_server" -H "accept: application/json" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -d "{ \"url\": \"https://<TARGET_ARTIFACTORY>/artifactory/api/access\<https://%3cTARGET_ARTIFACTORY%3e/artifactory/api/access/>"}" -i
*   A "204" HTTP response indicates that COT has been configured correctly. The "access-service.log" will also have log entry that says:
?  Verified circle of trust with server http://<TARGET_ARTIFACTORY>/artifactory/api/access<http://%3cTARGET_ARTIFACTORY%3e/artifactory/api/access> successfully

column2: we are seeing "400" and "404" HTTP errors during the validation of the federated repository. We will try to reproduce those errors to see what conditions might cause them.

I would suggest to create a change request for your documentation.  The documentation states

It is possible to override the default central server used by Artifactory to provide the checksums by adding the property artifactory.go.sumdb.url.override=https://... to your Artifactory's system properties<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Configuration+Files#ConfigurationFiles-SystemProperties>.

I think this is easily misinterpreted to imply that there is a non null 'default central server' that is configured (and perhaps sum.golang.org actually should be implemented as the default within artifactory as well )

column1: Thank you for contacting jFrog Support.

column2: please go through the below response:
you can run "export GOSUMDB="sum.golang.org"" to set the GOSUMDB to sum.golang.org.

column1: 2. Artifactory doesn't have any central server by default (null). If we would need to point the GOSUMDB to  sum.golang.com<https://sum.golang.com/>
column2: then we need to add artifactory.go.sumdb.url.override=https://sum.golang.org in Artifactory's system properties<https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Configuration+Files#ConfigurationFiles-SystemProperties>.

column1: I'm still looking through the logs but I'm seeing a couple key issues. The DB connection to Artifactory seems to be unstable. We see lots of

column2: 555 [http-nio-8081-exec-2444] [WARN ] (o.a.r.ArtifactoryResponseBase:155) - Client Closed Request 499: java.io.IOException: Broken pipe
636 [http-nio-8081-exec-2447] [WARN ] (o.a.r.ArtifactoryResponseBase:155) - Client Closed Request 499: java.io.IOException: Broken pipe
704 [http-nio-8081-exec-2160] [WARN ] (o.a.r.ArtifactoryResponseBase:155) - Client Closed Request 499: java.io.IOException: Broken pipe
748 [http-nio-8081-exec-1277] [WARN ] (o.a.r.ArtifactoryResponseBase:155) - Client Closed Request 499: java.io.IOException: Broken pipe
and we see various communication failures to the DB through logs such as the following
406 [http-nio-8081-exec-1607] [ERROR] (o.a.r.c.e.m.GlobalExceptionMapper:48) - Repository storage summary failed with exception: Can not read response from server. Expected to read 42 bytes
