column1: The last packet successfully received from the server was 11
column2: 553 milliseconds ago.  The last packet sent successfully to the server was 11

column1: Caused by: com.mysql.cj.exceptions.ConnectionIsClosedException: No operations allowed after connection closed.
Caused by: org.apache.tomcat.jdbc.pool.PoolExhaustedException: [http-nio-8081-exec-2123] Timeout: Pool empty. Unable to fetch a connection in 120 seconds
column2: none available[size:225; busy:225; idle:0; lastwait:120000].

column1: We also see the following message sometimes

column2: 063 [http-nio-8040-exec-93] [ERROR] (o.j.a.s.r.e.m.DefaultExceptionMapper:25) - General exception mapper caught:Could not save user

column1: Caused by: java.sql.SQLIntegrityConstraintViolationException: Duplicate entry '12104-12003' for key 'PRIMARY'
but it's more rare and unless it's holding up connections on the DB side it doesn't look to be the issue.
It could be as simple as increasing the DB connections in your db.properties as stated in https://jfrog.com/knowledge-base/artifactory-tuning-for-heavy-loads-versions-5-6/
column2: but currently I'm not sure if the issue is the connection pool or something in the connection between Artifactory and the DB. It does look like you're using the instance heavily (120k authentication requests in 2 hours) so I do recommend to increase the connection pool as we can see it's fully used up (the "[size:225; busy:225; idle:0; lastwait:120000]" line) and then we can monitor the DB connections and see which ones specifically are being held up
are you seeing any Memory or CPU spikes?

column1:
Insight service in Standalone MC will not be functional with Artifactory 7.27.3 and above”

Therefore, it is suggested to migrate Standalone MC to independent Insight and enable MC microservice in Artifactory.



First, to migrate platform deployments and license bucket from Standalone MC to MC microservice in Artifactory,

You should export MC database into a JSON file before shutting down Standalone MC.

eg.

curl -v -X PUT http://localhost:8082/mc/api/v1/system/backup/export -H Authorization: Bearer $TOKEN"
The backup.key and export.json will be created under  /opt/jfrog/mc/var/backup/mc/
To learn more about generating the admin token
column2: see Generating Admin Tokens.
to upgrade/change standalone Mission Control to Insight:

column1: 1.  Stop the existing Mission Control service.
2.  Disable Filebeat in the Artifactory and Xray system.yaml files and restart Artifactory

column2: see Installing Insight.

column1: Do not install Insight unless the standalone Mission Control service is completely down. There can be serious issues if you install Insight while the standalone Mission Control service is online.
4. Enable the Mission Control microservice in the Artifactory system.yaml file.
5. Enable Filebeat in the Artifactory and Xray system.yaml files and update the details of the Elasticsearch associated with Insight.
8.   Copy the backup.key and export.json under  /opt/jfrog/mc/var/backup/mc/  from Standalone MC to the Artifactory node inside the folder /var/opt/jfrog/artifactory/backup/mc/
9.   Rename the export.json file to import.json
10. Import the JSON file into Artifactory with the import API that reads the JSON file:
11. Refresh UI and you will see the platform deployment page and license bucket updated.

column2: I've combined the above process based on the following wikis -
if you have any questions

column2: Xray will detect the vulnerabilities based on the CVE data if there is no CVE associated with a package Xray will not detect the same. However
column3: you can block download/retrieval of a package by setting include/exclude patterns for remote repositories which will help in preventing Artifactory applications from searching these packages at the remote registry end as this will help in avoiding possible security risks.

column1: You can configure the include/exclude patterns for a repository by navigating from JFrog UI -> Administration -> Repositories -> Click on the repository-name -> Basic tab as shown in the below screenshot:

column1: We have an Artifactory QA environment that is active-active in two AWS regions. We set up SAML login in both HA clusters. "Auto redirect login link to SAML login" option is also enabled. Our IdP is provided a primary cross-region url to send back SAML response. We can log in to Artifactory from the primary cross-region url. However
column2: when I re-log in Artifactory after being logged-out due to inactivity
column3: SAML login occasionally fails. On failed logging cases
column4: I was still redirected to SAML login page as expected and was authenticated successfully (The PingID showed a successful verification UI page). After that
column5: the browser redirected me back to Artifactory and showed the error below at the URL path : "<Artifactory domain>/ui/api/v1/auth/saml/loginResponse" A temporary work around is to re-open and re-log in Artifactory in a new tab or in an incognito window. I'm thinking if it is possible that an Artifactory cluster in one region initiates the SAML login flow and the SAML response is sent back to Artifactory cluster in the other region.

column1: You can make use of AQL to get the list of files created a day ago in a repository this using REST API . As an example you can make use of the following:

column2: {"created" : {"$last" : "7d"}})

column1: Based on the results which has the property "path" and"name" you can perform a simple curl GET to download the files. For any further constructions on the query you can make use of this Wiki( https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Artifactory+Query+Language ).

column1: replications_errors table should be like in 7.5.8

It seemed that the following mysql_v224_change_replication_errors_to_node_event_errors.sql query was already executed (especially ALTER TABLE xxx parts )  partially before running RENAME table replication_errors

column2: there was no way to rollback to already executed schema change below 7.27.3 in Artifactory upgrade process.
you should restore the DB snapshot again to match the above replicatioin_errors table again.

column1: ALTER TABLE replication_errors CHANGE replication_key operation_key VARCHAR(255);
ALTER TABLE replication_errors CHANGE task_time event_time BIGINT NOT NULL;
ALTER TABLE replication_errors CHANGE task_type event_type SMALLINT NOT NULL;
ALTER TABLE replication_errors CHANGE task_path path VARCHAR(1344) NOT NULL;
ALTER TABLE replication_errors ADD event_category VARCHAR (225);
UPDATE node_events_errors SET event_category = 'REPLICATION' WHERE event_category IS NULL;
ALTER TABLE node_events_errors MODIFY event_category VARCHAR(255) NOT NULL;
UPDATE node_events_errors SET event_type = 1 WHERE event_type = 2;
I'd recommend rollback the DB snapshot to 7.5.8 and upgrading to 7.27.10 again.

column2: if you see that groups table is empty and manually drop the table (e.g  drop table groups; ) before upgrading 7.27.10 to avoid the initial syntax error as follows.

column1: Are you looking to not use your current load balancer anymore and are replacing it with an Nginx service? If this is the case you will only need one Nginx node.

If you are adding the Nginx nodes in addition to keeping the load balancer this may not solve the issue because as mentioned in our previous call there is most likely something in the Load Balancer that is not sending authentication properly.
If you still have a separate load balancer and are using Nginx for each Artifactory node you may remove this section.
## add HA entries when ha is configure
And to confirm since you have configured 8080; your load balancer is pointing to each of these nodes at 8080? For example
column2: the LB is redirecting the URL from  "http://artifactory-ha.bcbsfl.com" to 10.8.75.245:8080 (if the LB chooses this node).

column1: 2. No restart is needed for Artifactory.
3. Test the URL to see if everything is working as expected.
4&5. For Nginx you do not need to use HTTPS/SSL if SSL termination is occurring in the LoadBalancer. If you are replacing the LoadBalancer with Nginx
column2: yes
column3: you will need to use HTTP and SSL with Nginx and it will be using the certificate and key for "https://artifactory-ha.bcbsfl.com".

column1: 6. The default Nginx template will redirect requests with /artifactory in it to 8081.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utn0a:refTrue2021-12-01T22:55:55.000+000002s6900002S4Bb6AAF5006900003jcDZqAAMRe: [#185191] Unable to Pull Helm Charts from ArtifactoryI was able to figure out what's happening on the helm side that is causing the issue. It's a known issue that happens in particular with Artifactory. See the specific comment here: https://github.com/helm/helm/pull/9886

column3: this is last known working version3.6.1 - both 443 and not 443 both fail! This is where the issue first fails3.6.2 - 443 works
column4: not 443 fails. This is the same thing we see on latest

column1: The issue seems to be because when you run the helm index
column2: it's returning urls that always put in :443. Even if the repo add did not include :443. This causes problems because helm is treating it as a different domain and will not send credentials to prevent leaks. The insecure work around is to use --pass-credentials when you do the helm pull.

column1: I would agree with the link above
column2: that artifactory should not be adding :443 to the index if it wasn't added in the repo add. This may be fixed in helm
column3: though it might take some time. But if it's not fixed there
column4: I would consider this a bug in artifactory.

column6: separately stored files... But you have now clarified the topic from the DB perspective. Still it is not clear to me how the resource consumption difference looks like from application server perspective.As per my understanding
column7: if I have a zip file and the application stored it as single binary (checksum based) on the storage
column8: but I need to download single files from it (or just simply want to browse its content)
column9: I suppose that the application server needs to open this whole binary (which can be a large one with several thousands of files) first from the storage and needs to either unzip the contained requested files to be able to serve it (or when a browsing request is triggered
column10: the server has to query the big file for its content list - e.g. like "zipinfo -1 archive.zip" in the background).

column2: how much more costly (CPU/RAM on the Artifactory server) is this download of contained files from a big archive compared to the separately stored same files' download?
we can get back to the customer and safely recommend the usage of compressed zip archives
column3: instead of deploying millions of (mainly small) separate files. It will only have a positive effect on the overall resource consumption of the backend.

column2: Kalman

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utwBj:refTrue2021-12-01T23:02:12.000+000002s6900002S4BciAAF5006900003jdviOAAQ[#186498] Customers are frequently unable to complete ranged downloadsHello Adam

You will not see errors in logs with this change. multiReadEnabled just controls how many threads are used to download from the next provider ( S3 or NFS ) to cache. You might see a slight performance impact when files are downloaded from nfs to cache. However
column2: we are talking about a rare case when you have multiple download requests for the same file when it's cached for the first time. Please note that you want to increase your cache-fs size with this change
column3: because the default size is not good enough for your usage and you want to avoid frequent changes to cache in general. Thank you.

column1: As I understand the question - you are looking for a way to check what artifacts have a particular vulnerability. If so
column2: then some ways to do this are through the UI and through the REST API.  For the UI
column3: you can check the Ancestors of a vulnerable package to see the artifacts that include or depend on the package.  For the REST API - you can use the Find Component by CVE REST API can also be used to get the components by the CVEs it contains.

column1: ref:_00D20M3v0._500693utfZ2:refFalse2021-12-01T23:38:46.000+000002s6900002S4BiCAAV5006900003YgUD8AAN[#183675] Artifactory exits with an error code and dumps a thread in the logHello Ben
The issue is still being in the process of being reproduced by Prassanna and he will update you as soon as he is able.
I have taken a look at the Nginx configuration sent and the "fail_timeout" configuration appears to be quite low.
This setting according to Nginx documentation is:
the time during which the specified number of unsuccessful attempts to communicate with the server should happen to consider the server unavailable;
and the period of time the server will be considered unavailable.
This could mean that after it detects that the upstream node is down after 1 second it retrys that node again.
Could you try changing this configuration to 30 seconds and rerun the tests?

column1: The reason you need to up the storage is because the minimum storage requirements for Xray is 500gb
column2: and it usually takes 200-300gb from the initial DB sync and other files (https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/System+Requirements).

column1: 1) Xray shouldn't be taking down Artifactory
column2: can you send me the Artifactory logs when Artifactory went down as well as the Xray logs to see what was happening at the time?

column1: 2) Artifactory and Xray use separate databases
column2: and in most cases Xray shouldn't be installed on the same machine as well since they would compete for resources and ports and can cause various issues. It is possible to set up a machine with multiple DBs so to hold Artifactory's DB as well as Xray's DB
column3: but they are still separate and you need to make sure the machine has enough provisioned resources.

column1: 3) You can find this documentation here https://www.jfrog.com/confluence/display/JFROG/Creating+Xray+Policies+and+Rules
